enjamin Henry Latrobe buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:William Thornton buildings]]\n[[Category:Charles Bulfinch buildings]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival architecture in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "2601:248:102:10:68dd:9b23:94c7:a760", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Capitol"}
{"title_page": "Alaska Raceway Park", "text_new": "'''Alaska Raceway Park''' is a motorsports complex conducting races from Mother's Day to Labor Day.  Located near [[Butte, Alaska|Butte]], the [[Knik River]], and [[Knik Glacier]] at Mile 10.4 of the Old Glenn Highway, it is in [[Palmer, Alaska|Palmer]], about 41.5 miles northeast of [[Anchorage, Alaska]], US . Nearby 6,398-foot [[Pioneer Peak (Alaska)|Pioneer Peak]] looms over the finish line, providing a scenic racing venue recognized worldwide among race fans.  The track sits at an elevation of 63 feet above sea level, offering excellent air pressure for racing.\n\n== Drag strip ==\nThe 1/4-mile drag strip was opened in 1964 and run on leased land for the next 30 years by Lee and Fern Nelson and sons Ron and Larry as Polar Dragway.<ref>{{Cite web|title = At 50, Alaska Raceway Park still has tires burning and hearts pumping|url = http://www.adn.com/article/20140817/50-alaska-raceway-park-still-has-tires-burning-and-hearts-pumping|website = Alaska Dispatch News|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> The track has had several names over the years, including Thunder Valley Raceway, Valley Raceway, Big Valley Raceway, and Polar Raceway.  In November 1994, the racing operation was purchased from Lee Nelson and incorporated as Top End, Inc., held by a group of businesspeople who loved motorsport.  The group included Jack (Randy) Harris, Louie Kirk, John Childs, Jerry Schreiner, Gregg Gunnarson, and Kristen Kinn, and the name was changed to Alaska Raceway Park.  Earl Lackey purchased Jerry Schreiner's shares in 1995.  Top End completed extensive changes:  environmental cleanup, installation of an entrance via Sullivan Road, installation of new bleachers and sound system, and re-roof of all buildings.\n\nThe drag strip become the only Alaska [[International Hot Rod Association|IHRA]] member track<ref>{{Cite web|title = International Hot Rod Association - Tracks|url = http://www.ihra.com/ihra-tracks/tracks|website = www.ihra.com|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> on March 1, 1995, through the efforts of Gregg Gunnarson.  In 2003, Alaska Raceway Park was recognized by IHRA as Track of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|title = Motorsports Addiction Race Results & News - 2004|url = http://www.motorsports-addiction.com/news04_ihra1.html|website = www.motorsports-addiction.com|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> for showing \"positive growth and success on the track.\"  In 2012 IHRA recognized Alaska Raceway Park as the Summit SuperSeries Track of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|title = Palm Beach International Raceway - 2012 IHRA TRACK OF THE YEAR AWARDED TO PBIR|url = http://www.racepbir.com/component/k2/item/755-pbir-awarded-ihra-track-of-the-year|website = www.racepbir.com|access-date = 2016-02-14}}</ref> for Division 6.\nIn Fall 1998, Earl and Karen Lackey bought the corporate stock from the other owners and, with their daughter, Michelle Lackey Maynor, remain the current owners.  They continue track improvements, including new bleachers on the pit side, remodeling the main building (snack bar and lounge), adding a gift shop, enlarging the work shop, adding improved firefighting and track-cleaning equipment, paving the staging area and pit parking, and installing a separate entry gate for racers.\n\nIn April 2000, after 35 winters and thousands of rounds of racing, the track surface was weathered and frost-heaved.  A new audio system with a radio transmitter was also installed before the massive cooperative effort to grind up the old track, lay a new bed using laser-controlled machinery, constructing a heated 300-foot concrete launch pad, then laying down 4,100 feet of asphalt.  Much of the work was accomplished through volunteers, with assistance from the Operator's Union, VECO, Denali Concrete, and a donation of emulsion from Tesoro Refining and Marketing.  On May 21, 2000, a new state-of-the-art computerized timing system was put into use.\n\nIn 2002, the Lackeys successfully purchased the 155 acres previously leased from the State of Alaska, as well as an adjoining 27 acres from the [[Matanuska-Susitna Borough, Alaska|Matanuska-Susitna Borough]].  This purchase made the track's status permanent and provided room for parking.\n\n=== Announcers ===\nOver the years there have been many voices floating over the drag strip P.A. system:  \"Big Daddy\" Dave, Jerry Pierce, Steve Byrd, Rodney Villanueva, \"Big Schwag\" Brett Wagner, \"Chatterbox\" Christa Mayfield, Alex Van Nice, Justin Giles and Sean Farris.\n\n== Oval track ==\nAn adjacent 1/4-mile dirt oval track was operated from 1980 to 1986.\n\nIn 2016 a [https://web.archive.org/web/20160126211945/http://www.alaskaracewaypark.com/oval-track new 1/3-mile asphalt oval track] is debuting, sponsored in part by Tesoro Refining and Marketing, Pruhs Construction, Soper's Concrete, Valley Block and Concrete, E-Terra, Acutek Geomatics, New Horizons Telecom, and J.D. Steel Co.  The oval track was sanctioned in February 2016 as a home track by [[NASCAR]] in its [[Whelen All-American Series]], consequently, the track became the first NASCAR-sanctioned track at Alaska<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nascar.nbcsports.com/2016/06/02/alaska-gets-first-nascar-sanctioned-racetrack-will-host-whelen-series/ |title=Alaska gets first NASCAR-sanctioned racetrack, will host Whelen (All-American) Series |first=Jerry |last=Bonkowski |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=June 2, 2016 |accessdate=April 29, 2020}}</ref> and also the northernmost NASCAR-sanctioned track in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|title = NASCAR\u2019S LAST FRONTIER|url =https://www.nascar.com/long-form/nascar-alaska-track-frontier-feature/|website=NASCAR.com |publisher=NASCAR Digital Media, LLC.|date= September 26, 2019|access-date = April 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNotable [[NASCAR]] drivers, like: [[Jordan Anderson (racing driver)|Jordan Anderson]], [[Jake Griffin]], [[Bobby Reuse]], [[Roger Reuse]] and [[Joe Hudson (racing driver)|Joe Hudson]] already competed at Alaska Raceway Park.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Alaska Raceway Park all-time drivers |url =http://www.raceak.com/drivers/?c=1061&view=archive&y=2019#archive|website=raceak.com |publisher=Alaska Raceway Park|date= September 28, 2019|access-date = April 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Keith McGee]] (the first-ever driver from Alaska to race in any series in NASCAR) also ran at the track.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Keith McGee race results' at Alaska Raceway Park |url =http://www.raceak.com/profile/schedule/?r=81315&rt=driver |website=raceak.com |publisher=Alaska Raceway Park|date= September 28, 2019|access-date = April 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.akracewaypark.com Alaska Raceway Park official website]\n* [https://hometracks.nascar.com/tracks/alaska-raceway-park/ Alaska Raceway Park page info at NASCAR Home Tracks]\n\n{{coord|61|31|30|N|149|01|28|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:IHRA drag racing venues]]\n[[Category:NASCAR tracks]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Matanuska-Susitna Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Matanuska-Susitna Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Motorsport venues in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Alaska]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alaska Raceway Park''' is a motorsports complex conducting races from Mother's Day to Labor Day.  Located near [[Butte, Alaska|Butte]], the [[Knik River]], and [[Knik Glacier]] at Mile 10.4 of the Old Glenn Highway, it is in [[Palmer, Alaska|Palmer]], about 41.5 miles northeast of [[Anchorage, Alaska]], US . Nearby 6,398-foot [[Pioneer Peak (Alaska)|Pioneer Peak]] looms over the finish line, providing a scenic racing venue recognized worldwide among race fans.  The track sits at an elevation of 63 feet above sea level, offering excellent air pressure for racing.\n\n== Drag strip ==\nThe 1/4-mile drag strip was opened in 1964 and run on leased land for the next 30 years by Lee and Fern Nelson and sons Ron and Larry as Polar Dragway.<ref>{{Cite web