{"title_page": "W. Graham Claytor Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American government official}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image        = W. Graham Claytor 1984.jpg\n|office       = President and CEO of [[Amtrak]]\n|term_start   = 1982\n|term_end     = 1993\n|predecessor  = [[Alan Stephenson Boyd]]\n|successor    = Thomas Downs\n|office1      = [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense]]\n|term_start1  = August 21, 1979\n|term_end1    = January 16, 1981\n|president1   = [[Jimmy Carter]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Charles Duncan Jr.|Charles Duncan]]\n|successor1   = [[Frank Carlucci]]\n|office2      = [[United States Secretary of the Navy]]\n|president2   = [[Jimmy Carter]]\n|term_start2  = February 14, 1977\n|term_end2    = August 24, 1979\n|predecessor2 = [[J. William Middendorf]]\n|successor2   = [[Edward Hidalgo]]\n|birth_name=William Graham Claytor Jr.\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1912|3|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Roanoke, Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1994|5|14|1912|3|14}}\n|death_place  = [[Bradenton, Florida]], U.S.\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Frances Claytor\n|education    = [[University of Virginia]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]])}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears = 1941\u20131946\n|rank         = [[File:U.S. Navy O-4 insignia.svg|20px]]  [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n|battles      = [[World War II]]\n}}\n'''William Graham Claytor Jr.''' (March 14, 1912 \u2013 May 14, 1994) was an American [[lawyer]], [[naval officer]], and [[railroad]], transportation and defense administrator for the [[United States]] government, working under the administrations of three US presidents.\n\nHe is remembered for his actions as the captain of the [[destroyer escort]] {{USS|Cecil J. Doyle|DE-368|6}}, during [[World War II]] which helped to save 317 lives during the {{USS|Indianapolis|CA-35|6}} tragedy. Over 30 years later, Claytor's moderate actions on behalf of the rights of [[Women in the United States Navy|female]] and [[Sexual orientation and the United States military|gay]] service personnel as [[Secretary of the Navy]] were considered progressive for the time. He is also credited with a distinguished transportation career, including ten years as president of the [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]] and 11 years as the head of [[Amtrak]], guiding the passenger railroad through a particularly difficult period in its history. He was named the Virginian of the Year in 1977.<ref name=\"viriginayera\"/>\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nClaytor was born in [[Roanoke, Virginia]] on March 14, 1912, and grew up in both [[Virginia]] and [[Philadelphia]]. He was the son of [[Gertrude Harris Boatwright Claytor]], a lyric poet, and [[W. Graham Claytor]] (1886\u20131971), who was vice-president of [[Appalachian Power]].\n\nClaytor graduated from the [[University of Virginia]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] in 1933. He then graduated from [[Harvard Law School]] ''[[summa cum laude]]'' in 1936. He then clerked for [[Learned Hand]], Judge of the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]]. He then moved to Washington, D.C., to become law clerk to U.S. Supreme Court Associate Justice [[Louis Brandeis]] before joining the prestigious [[Washington, DC|Washington]] law firm [[Covington and Burling]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===World War II \u2014 USS ''Indianapolis'' tragedy===\n\nIn 1940, soon after the start of [[World War II]], 28-year-old Claytor attempted to enlist, but was initially rejected by the [[United States Navy]] as being too old.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} He finally joined under a special provision, based upon his previous experience in sports boating. He was assigned to the [[Pacific Ocean theater of World War II|Pacific Theater]].\n\nLate in the war, Claytor became commanding officer of the destroyer escort {{USS|Cecil J. Doyle|DE-368|6}} on patrol in the [[Pacific Ocean]].<ref name=\"proceedings\">Marks (April 1981), pp. 48\u201350.</ref> In August 1945, Claytor sped without orders {{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} to investigate reports of men floating in the water. As ''Cecil J. Doyle'' approached the area at night, Claytor turned the ship's searchlights on the water and straight up on low clouds, lighting up the night, despite the risk of exposing his ship to possible attack by Japanese submarines.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> These actions facilitated the rescue of the survivors of the sunken [[cruiser]] {{USS|Indianapolis|CA-35|6}}.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/>\n\n''Indianapolis'' had been on a secret mission, and due to a communications error, had not been reported as overdue (or missing). An estimated 900 men survived the sinking, but spent days floating in life jackets trying to fight off sharks. While only 317 were rescued out of a crew of 1199 who were aboard ''Indianapolis'', Claytor's actions were widely credited by survivors with preventing an even greater loss of life.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\n===Legal practice and Southern Railway===\n{{See also|Southern Railway (US)}}\nAfter World War II, he resumed practice of law in Washington, D.C. He became an officer of the [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]] in 1963, serving as president from 1967\u20131977. Notwithstanding his legal background, Claytor was known as an \"operations\" man, often riding the company's trains, monitoring and questioning performance.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} In contrast to his predecessor, [[D. William Brosnan]], Claytor was an \"employee's President,\" often chatting with the crews of the trains on which he rode, actively soliciting their suggestions on how to make the railroad run better. He carried this attitude with him during his later service as the President of Amtrak.\n\n===U.S. Government service===\n{{See also|Secretary of the Navy}}\nClaytor served as the [[Secretary of the Navy]] under President [[Jimmy Carter]] from 1977<ref name=\"csm-shutt1\">{{cite news | first = Anne | last = Shutt | title = In Short\u2026 | url = http://www.csmonitor.com/1982/0611/061125.html | work = Christian Science Monitor | publisher = [[First Church of Christ, Scientist, Boston|First Church of Christ, Scientist]] | location = [[Boston, Massachusetts]] | date = 1982-06-11 | accessdate = 2008-06-12}}</ref> to 1979.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} He is credited with leading the [[United States Navy]] into its first recognition of [[Equal opportunity|women's right to serve on ships]] and of [[gay rights|rights of gays]] to leave the service without criminal records. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} His positions were considered by activists to be progressive for the time, leading to further progress years later in these controversial issues.\n\nIn 1979, he was appointed to the position of [[Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} While serving as Deputy Defense Secretary, Claytor's military assistant was General [[Colin Powell]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nIn the summer of 1979, he took a brief leave from the [[U.S. Department of Defense|Defense Department]] to serve as [[Secretary of Transportation|Acting Secretary of Transportation]] in Carter's Cabinet. His service at the Transportation Department bridged the tenures of Secretary [[Brock Adams]] and Secretary [[Neil Goldschmidt]].\n\n===Amtrak===\n{{See also|Amtrak}}\nIn 1982, Claytor came out of retirement to lead [[Amtrak]]. He was recruited and strongly supported by [[John H. Riley]], an attorney who was also the head of the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) under the [[Ronald W. Reagan|Reagan Administration]] from 1983 to 1989.\n\nClaytor maintained a good relationship with the [[U.S. Congress]] during his 11 years in the position. Within 7 years of being under Claytor's leadership, Amtrak was generating enough money to cover 72 percent of its $1.7 billion operating budget by 1989, up from 48 percent in 1981.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Alpert |first1=Mark |date=1989-10-23 |title=Still Chugging |journal=Fortune |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher= |doi= |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1989/10/23/72601/index.htm |accessdate=2011-05-30}}</ref> This was achieved mainly through vigorous cost cutting and aggressive marketing. He is credited with bringing political and operational stability to the nation's passenger train network, keeping the railroad functioning properly despite repeated attempts by the administrations of Reagan and his successor [[George H.W. Bush]] to eliminate its funding.\n\nClaytor retired from Amtrak in 1993.\n\n==Legacy and heritage==\nClaytor was named the Virginian of the Year in 1977.<ref name=\"viriginayera\">{{cite web| publisher=Virginia Press Association| url=http://www.vpa.net/association_services/virginian_of_year.htm| title=VPA's Virginian of the Year| accessdate=2007-08-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930080039/http://www.vpa.net/association_services/virginian_of_year.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-30}}</ref> In 1989, he was named [[Railroader of the Year]] by ''[[Railway Age]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"Railroader of the Year\">{{cite journal| journal=Railway Age| title=Hunter Harrison presented Railroader of the Year Award \u2013 Rail Update \u2013 executive vice president and chief operating officer of Canadian National/Illinois Central \u2013 Brief Article| url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1215/is_4_203/ai_90886380|date=April 2002| accessdate=2007-01-13}}</ref>\n\nHe was the brother of [[Robert B. Claytor]], who became president of [[Norfolk and Western Railway]] in 1981 and was the first chairman and CEO of [[Norfolk Southern]] after it was formed by merger with the Southern Railway System in 1982. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} Robert B. Claytor is best remembered by many railfans for reactivating [[Norfolk and Western Railway]]'s steam program, which rebuilt [[steam locomotive]]s J-611 and A-1218 at the [[Roanoke Shops]] at [[Roanoke, Virginia]], and operated excursion trips. Claytor Jr. would occasionally take the throttle as engineer with his brother on the steam excursions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nClaytor died on May 14, 1994.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |title=W. Graham Claytor, Architect Of Amtrak Growth, Dies at 82 |first=Richard D. |last=Lyons |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/15/obituaries/w-graham-claytor-architect-of-amtrak-growth-dies-at-82.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=1994-05-15 |accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt Amtrak's [[Washington, DC]] [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] a passenger concourse was renamed \"Claytor Concourse\" in his honor.<ref name=NYT/>\n\n\"The Claytor Brothers: Virginians Building America's Railroad\" is a semi-permanent exhibit at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Claytor Brothers\u2014Virginians Building America's Railroad|work=Exhibits|publisher=[[Virginia Museum of Transportation]]|url=http://www.vmt.org/visit/exhibits |access-date=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railroad executives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Marks, R. Adrian |title=America was Well Represented |publisher=United States Naval Institute Proceedings |date=April 1981}}\n*{{White - America's most noteworthy railroaders}}\n* [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?r103:E18MY4-295: quotes from article by journalist Don Phillips of the ''Washington Post'' in a \"Tribute to W. Graham Claytor Jr.\" published May, 1994]\n* [http://www.ussindianapolis.org/intro.htm Survivors Groups official website for the U.S.S. ''Indianapolis'']\n* {{cite book| author=Wrinn, Jim| title=Steam's Camelot: Southern and Norfolk Southern Excursions in Color| year=2000| publisher=TLC Publishing| isbn=1-883089-56-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|grahamclaytor}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[D. William Brosnan]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=President of [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]]| years=1967\u20131977}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Stanley Crane|L. Stanley Crane]]<ref name=\"NAE\">[http://www.nae.edu/29537.aspx L. Stanley Crane, elected in 1978 as a member of the United States National Academy of Engineering]</ref><ref name=\"crane\">''L. Stanley Crane'' (born in [[Cincinnati]], 1915) raised in Washington, lived in [[McLean, Virginia|McLean]] before moving to [[Philadelphia]] in 1981. He began his career with [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] after graduating from [[The George Washington University]] with a [[chemical engineering]] degree in 1938. He worked for the railroad, except for a stint from 1959 to 1961 with the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], until reaching the company's mandatory retirement age in 1980. ''Crane'' went to [[Conrail]] in 1981 after a distinguished career that had seen him rise to the position of CEO at the Southern Railway. He died of pneumonia on July 15, 2003 at a hospice in [[Boynton Beach, Florida|Boynton Beach]], [[Fla.]]</ref>}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Alan Stephenson Boyd]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=President of [[Amtrak]]| years=1982\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft| after=Thomas Downs}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[J. William Middendorf]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[United States Secretary of the Navy]]| years=\tFebruary 14, 1977 \u2013 August 24, 1979}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Edward Hidalgo]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Charles Duncan Jr.]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense]]| years=1979\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Frank Carlucci]]}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Darius W. Gaskins Jr.]] ([[Burlington Northern Railway|BN]])}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[Railroader of the Year|Modern Railways magazine's<br/>Man of the Year]]| years=1989}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Arnold B. McKinnon]] ([[Norfolk Southern|NS]])}}\n\n{{end}}\n\n{{USSecNavy}}\n{{USDepSecDef}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Claytor, W. Graham Jr.}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:American railroad executives of the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Roanoke, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Virginia]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of the Navy]]\n[[Category:United States Deputy Secretaries of Defense]]\n[[Category:Amtrak presidents]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of Judge Learned Hand]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Southern Railway (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:American railroaders]]\n[[Category:People associated with Covington & Burling]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American government official}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image        = W. Graham Claytor 1984.jpg\n|office       = President and CEO of [[Amtrak]]\n|term_start   = 1982\n|term_end     = 1993\n|predecessor  = [[Alan Stephenson Boyd]]\n|successor    = Thomas Downs\n|office1      = [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense]]\n|term_start1  = August 21, 1979\n|term_end1    = January 16, 1981\n|president1   = [[Jimmy Carter]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Charles Duncan Jr.|Charles Duncan]]\n|successor1   = [[Frank Carlucci]]\n|office2      = [[United States Secretary of the Navy]]\n|president2   = [[Jimmy Carter]]\n|term_start2  = February 14, 1977\n|term_end2    = August 24, 1979\n|predecessor2 = [[J. William Middendorf]]\n|successor2   = [[Edward Hidalgo]]\n|birth_name=William Graham Claytor Jr.\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1912|3|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Roanoke, Virginia]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1994|5|14|1912|3|14}}\n|death_place  = [[Bradenton, Florida]], U.S.\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Frances Claytor\n|education    = [[University of Virginia]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]])}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears = 1941\u20131946\n|rank         = [[File:U.S. Navy O-4 insignia.svg|20px]]  [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n|battles      = [[World War II]]\n}}\n'''William Graham Claytor Jr.''' (March 14, 1912 \u2013 May 14, 1994) was an American [[lawyer]], [[naval officer]], and [[railroad]], transportation and defense administrator for the [[United States]] government, working under the administrations of three US presidents.\n\nHe is remembered for his actions as the captain of the [[destroyer escort]] {{USS|Cecil J. Doyle|DE-368|6}}, during [[World War II]] which helped to save 317 lives during the {{USS|Indianapolis|CA-35|6}} tragedy. Over 30 years later, Claytor's moderate actions on behalf of the rights of [[Women in the United States Navy|female]] and [[Sexual orientation and the United States military|gay]] service personnel as [[Secretary of the Navy]] were considered progressive for the time. He is also credited with a distinguished transportation career, including ten years as president of the [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]] and 11 years as the head of [[Amtrak]], guiding the passenger railroad through a particularly difficult period in its history. He was named the Virginian of the Year in 1977.<ref name=\"viriginayera\"/>\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nClaytor was born in [[Roanoke, Virginia]] on March 14, 1912, and grew up in both [[Virginia]] and [[Philadelphia]]. He was the son of [[Gertrude Harris Boatwright Claytor]], a lyric poet, and [[W. Graham Claytor]] (1886\u20131971), who was vice-president of [[Appalachian Power]].\n\nClaytor graduated from the [[University of Virginia]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] in 1933. He then graduated from [[Harvard Law School]] ''[[summa cum laude]]'' in 1936. He then clerked for [[Learned Hand]], Judge of the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]]. He then moved to Washington, D.C., to become law clerk to U.S. Supreme Court Associate Justice [[Louis Brandeis]] before joining the prestigious [[Washington, DC|Washington]] law firm [[Covington and Burling]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===World War II \u2014 USS ''Indianapolis'' tragedy===\n\nIn 1940, soon after the start of [[World War II]], 28-year-old Claytor attempted to enlist, but was initially rejected by the [[United States Navy]] as being too old.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} He finally joined under a special provision, based upon his previous experience in sports boating. He was assigned to the [[Pacific Ocean theater of World War II|Pacific Theater]].\n\nLate in the war, Claytor became commanding officer of the destroyer escort {{USS|Cecil J. Doyle|DE-368|6}} on patrol in the [[Pacific Ocean]].<ref name=\"proceedings\">Marks (April 1981), pp. 48\u201350.</ref> In August 1945, Claytor sped without orders {{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} to investigate reports of men floating in the water. As ''Cecil J. Doyle'' approached the area at night, Claytor turned the ship's searchlights on the water and straight up on low clouds, lighting up the night, despite the risk of exposing his ship to possible attack by Japanese submarines.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> These actions facilitated the rescue of the survivors of the sunken [[cruiser]] {{USS|Indianapolis|CA-35|6}}.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/>\n\n''Indianapolis'' had been on a secret mission, and due to a communications error, had not been reported as overdue (or missing). An estimated 900 men survived the sinking, but spent days floating in life jackets trying to fight off sharks. While only 317 were rescued out of a crew of 1199 who were aboard ''Indianapolis'', Claytor's actions were widely credited by survivors with preventing an even greater loss of life.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\n===Legal practice and Southern Railway===\n{{See also|Southern Railway (US)}}\nAfter World War II, he resumed practice of law in Washington DC. He became an officer of the [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]] in 1963, serving as president from 1967\u20131977. Notwithstanding his legal background, Claytor was known as an \"operations\" man, often riding the company's trains, monitoring and questioning performance.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} In contrast to his predecessor, [[D. William Brosnan]], Mr. Claytor was an \"employee's President,\" often chatting with the crews of the trains on which he rode, actively soliciting their suggestions on how to make the railroad run better. He carried this attitude with him during his later service as the President of Amtrak.\n\n===U.S. Government service===\n{{See also|Secretary of the Navy}}\nClaytor served as the [[Secretary of the Navy]] under President [[Jimmy Carter]] from 1977<ref name=\"csm-shutt1\">{{cite news | first = Anne | last = Shutt | title = In Short\u2026 | url = http://www.csmonitor.com/1982/0611/061125.html | work = Christian Science Monitor | publisher = [[First Church of Christ, Scientist, Boston|First Church of Christ, Scientist]] | location = [[Boston, Massachusetts]] | date = 1982-06-11 | accessdate = 2008-06-12}}</ref> to 1979.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} He is credited with leading the [[United States Navy]] into its first recognition of [[Equal opportunity|women's right to serve on ships]] and of [[gay rights|rights of gays]] to leave the service without criminal records. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} His positions were considered by activists to be progressive for the time, leading to further progress years later in these controversial issues.\n\nIn 1979, he was appointed to the position of [[Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} While serving as Deputy Defense Secretary, Claytor's military assistant was General [[Colin Powell]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nIn the summer of 1979, he took a brief leave from the [[U.S. Department of Defense|Defense Department]] to serve as [[Secretary of Transportation|Acting Secretary of Transportation]] in Carter's Cabinet. His service at the Transportation Department bridged the tenures of Secretary [[Brock Adams]] and Secretary [[Neil Goldschmidt]].\n\n===Amtrak===\n{{See also|Amtrak}}\nIn 1982, Claytor came out of retirement to lead [[Amtrak]]. He was recruited and strongly supported by [[John H. Riley]], an attorney who was also the head of the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] (FRA) under the [[Ronald W. Reagan|Reagan Administration]] from 1983 to 1989.\n\nClaytor maintained a good relationship with the [[U.S. Congress]] during his 11 years in the position. Within 7 years of being under Claytor's leadership, Amtrak was generating enough money to cover 72 percent of its $1.7 billion operating budget by 1989, up from 48 percent in 1981.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Alpert |first1=Mark |date=1989-10-23 |title=Still Chugging |journal=Fortune |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher= |doi= |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1989/10/23/72601/index.htm |accessdate=2011-05-30}}</ref> This was achieved mainly through vigorous cost cutting and aggressive marketing. He is credited with bringing political and operational stability to the nation's passenger train network, keeping the railroad functioning properly despite repeated attempts by the administrations of Reagan and his successor [[George H.W. Bush]] to eliminate its funding.\n\nClaytor retired from Amtrak in 1993.\n\n==Legacy and heritage==\nClaytor was named the Virginian of the Year in 1977.<ref name=\"viriginayera\">{{cite web| publisher=Virginia Press Association| url=http://www.vpa.net/association_services/virginian_of_year.htm| title=VPA's Virginian of the Year| accessdate=2007-08-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930080039/http://www.vpa.net/association_services/virginian_of_year.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-30}}</ref> In 1989, he was named [[Railroader of the Year]] by ''[[Railway Age]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"Railroader of the Year\">{{cite journal| journal=Railway Age| title=Hunter Harrison presented Railroader of the Year Award \u2013 Rail Update \u2013 executive vice president and chief operating officer of Canadian National/Illinois Central \u2013 Brief Article| url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1215/is_4_203/ai_90886380|date=April 2002| accessdate=2007-01-13}}</ref>\n\nHe was the brother of [[Robert B. Claytor]], who became president of [[Norfolk and Western Railway]] in 1981 and was the first chairman and CEO of [[Norfolk Southern]] after it was formed by merger with the Southern Railway System in 1982. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} Robert B. Claytor is best remembered by many railfans for reactivating [[Norfolk and Western Railway]]'s steam program, which rebuilt [[steam locomotive]]s J-611 and A-1218 at the [[Roanoke Shops]] at [[Roanoke, Virginia]], and operated excursion trips. Claytor Jr. would occasionally take the throttle as engineer with his brother on the steam excursions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nClaytor died on May 14, 1994.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |title=W. Graham Claytor, Architect Of Amtrak Growth, Dies at 82 |first=Richard D. |last=Lyons |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/15/obituaries/w-graham-claytor-architect-of-amtrak-growth-dies-at-82.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=1994-05-15 |accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt Amtrak's [[Washington, DC]] [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] a passenger concourse was renamed \"Claytor Concourse\" in his honor.<ref name=NYT/>\n\n\"The Claytor Brothers: Virginians Building America's Railroad\" is a semi-permanent exhibit at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Claytor Brothers\u2014Virginians Building America's Railroad|work=Exhibits|publisher=[[Virginia Museum of Transportation]]|url=http://www.vmt.org/visit/exhibits |access-date=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railroad executives]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Marks, R. Adrian |title=America was Well Represented |publisher=United States Naval Institute Proceedings |date=April 1981}}\n*{{White - America's most noteworthy railroaders}}\n* [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?r103:E18MY4-295: quotes from article by journalist Don Phillips of the ''Washington Post'' in a \"Tribute to W. Graham Claytor Jr.\" published May, 1994]\n* [http://www.ussindianapolis.org/intro.htm Survivors Groups official website for the U.S.S. ''Indianapolis'']\n* {{cite book| author=Wrinn, Jim| title=Steam's Camelot: Southern and Norfolk Southern Excursions in Color| year=2000| publisher=TLC Publishing| isbn=1-883089-56-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|grahamclaytor}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[D. William Brosnan]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=President of [[Southern Railway (US)|Southern Railway]]| years=1967\u20131977}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Stanley Crane|L. Stanley Crane]]<ref name=\"NAE\">[http://www.nae.edu/29537.aspx L. Stanley Crane, elected in 1978 as a member of the United States National Academy of Engineering]</ref><ref name=\"crane\">''L. Stanley Crane'' (born in [[Cincinnati]], 1915) raised in Washington, lived in [[McLean, Virginia|McLean]] before moving to [[Philadelphia]] in 1981. He began his career with [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] after graduating from [[The George Washington University]] with a [[chemical engineering]] degree in 1938. He worked for the railroad, except for a stint from 1959 to 1961 with the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], until reaching the company's mandatory retirement age in 1980. ''Crane'' went to [[Conrail]] in 1981 after a distinguished career that had seen him rise to the position of CEO at the Southern Railway. He died of pneumonia on July 15, 2003 at a hospice in [[Boynton Beach, Florida|Boynton Beach]], [[Fla.]]</ref>}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Alan Stephenson Boyd]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=President of [[Amtrak]]| years=1982\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft| after=Thomas Downs}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[J. William Middendorf]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[United States Secretary of the Navy]]| years=\tFebruary 14, 1977 \u2013 August 24, 1979}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Edward Hidalgo]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Charles Duncan Jr.]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense]]| years=1979\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Frank Carlucci]]}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Darius W. Gaskins Jr.]] ([[Burlington Northern Railway|BN]])}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[Railroader of the Year|Modern Railways magazine's<br/>Man of the Year]]| years=1989}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Arnold B. McKinnon]] ([[Norfolk Southern|NS]])}}\n\n{{end}}\n\n{{USSecNavy}}\n{{USDepSecDef}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Claytor, W. Graham Jr.}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:American railroad executives of the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Roanoke, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Virginia]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of the Navy]]\n[[Category:United States Deputy Secretaries of Defense]]\n[[Category:Amtrak presidents]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of Judge Learned Hand]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Southern Railway (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:American railroaders]]\n[[Category:People associated with Covington & Burling]]\n", "name_user": "Cyanolinguophile", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegal practice and Southern Railway", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._Graham_Claytor_J