{"title_page": "Nishapur train disaster", "text_new": "{{Infobox public transit accident|name=Nishapur train disaster|image=File:\u0641\u0627\u062c\u0639\u0647 \u0642\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u0627\u0628\u0648\u0631 - panoramio.jpg|coordinates={{coord|36.0987|58.9715|type:event|display=inline,title}}|date={{Start date|2004|02|18|df=yes}}|country=[[Iran]]|location=Khayyam|deaths=295|location_city=Nishapur|caption=Khayyam burning after the incident|image_alt=In twilight against snow capped mountains, two firefighters walk through a field flanked by burning rubble of the village|injuries=460|cause=Runaway rail cars|type=Derailment}}{{no footnotes|date=February 2011}}The '''Neishapur train disaster''' was a large explosion in the village of [[Khayyam,_Nishapur|Khayyam]], near [[Nishapur]]  in [[Iran]], on 18 February 2004. Nearly 300 people were killed<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3498851.stm|title=Iran train blast kills hundreds|date=2004-02-18|access-date=2020-04-29|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3487290.stm|title='Error' caused Iran train blast|date=2004-02-25|access-date=2020-04-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the entire village destroyed when runaway train wagons crashed into the community in the middle of the night and exploded, resulting as Iran's deadliest rail disaster to ever occur.\n\n==Beginning of incident==\n\nThe incident began in the city of Nishapur, where 51 railway wagons carrying sulphur, fertiliser, petrol and cotton wool broke loose from their siding at Abu Muslim Station, and rolled down the track for about twenty kilometers, until they derailed and rolled down an embankment into the town of Khayyam.<ref name=\":1\" /> There was nobody manning the wagons, or on board at the time of the crash, but local rescue services from all the neighbouring towns arrived to rescue anybody who might have been trapped inside, and to extinguish several minor fires which had broken out in the wreckage.\n\n==Chemical leak==\n\nThe substances in the wagons were all highly explosive or flammable (although the Iranian railway authority had not classed any of them as \"dangerous\" before the incident), and had leaked following the crash. As the small fires spread, a large crowd of local people, including several local politicians and senior railway officials, gathered to watch the emergency operation.\n\n==Explosion==\n\nDuring the cleanup operation, the cargo of the wagons exploded - reportedly at the equivalent of 180 tons of [[trinitrotoluene|TNT]]<ref name=\":1\" /> - demolishing Khayyam, badly damaging the nearby towns of [[Eyshabad, Nishapur|Eyshabad]], [[Dehnow, Nishapur|Dehnow]] and [[Taqiabad, Nishapur|Taqiabad]], and being felt in the city of [[Mashhad]], 70 kilometers away. The entire village was destroyed, and all of the local emergency services and government personnel were killed or seriously injured in the blast. The wreckage of the train and village continued to burn and explode for several days, despite the cold weather.\n\n==Death toll==\n\nState authorities identified 295 confirmed killed and over 460 injured, including 182 rescue workers and state officials.\n\n==Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps==\nFollowing the blast, troops from the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] were called in and were able to maintain security, whilst hundreds of rescue workers were brought in to help with the injured, the trapped, the missing and the dead.{{Citation Needed|date=September 2011}} Four villages were later described as \"totally destroyed\".{{Citation Needed|date=September 2011}}\n\n==Cause==\n\nInitial reports that \"earth tremors\"<ref name=\":0\" /> started the wagons rolling have since been discredited, and a thorough investigation has so far failed to discover how exactly the wagons were able to travel from Nishapur to Khayyam on their own, why so many highly flammable cargoes were stored and transported together, and why the details of the crash weren't discovered sooner, perhaps in time to arrange an evacuation. A statement from the Iranian Transport Minister [[Ahmad Khorram]] shortly after the incident reported that natural causes could not have caused the disaster, and that an investigation was under way to determine whether it was incompetence or malice by railway staff that allowed the wagons to come loose from where they were parked.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment]] - a 2013 derailment of fuel train and subsequent fire and explosions in the core of a Canadian town, also caused by railcars parked on an incline becoming loose.\n* [[Viareggio train derailment]] - a 2009 derailment of a fuel train in Viareggio, central Italy that caused explosions and fire which killed 32 people.\n* [[Soham rail disaster]] - a 1944 fire and subsequent explosion of an ammunition train near Soham, England.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3487290.stm BBC Report on Aftermath]\n*[http://www.irantour.org/Iran/news/iran_train_blast_neyshaboor_mashad.html Immediate Iranian statement]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/iran/story/0,12858,1150689,00.html Guardian News Report]\n*[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-02/19/content_307559.htm China Daily News Report]\n*[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/4300626 MSNBC News Report]\n*{{in lang|fa}} [http://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/iran/story/2007/11/071127_mf_neyshabur.shtml People responsible for Nishapur train disaster announced by court]\n\n{{2004 railway accidents}}\n\n[[Category:Explosions in 2004]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 2004]]\n[[Category:Derailments in Iran]]\n[[Category:2004 in Iran]]\n[[Category:Explosions in Iran]]\n[[Category:Nishapur|Train disaster]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Iran]]\n[[Category:History of Nishapur]]\n[[Category:Runaway train disasters]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Islamic Republic of Iran Railways]]\n[[Category:February 2004 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Train and subway fires]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox public transit accident|name=Nishapur train disaster|image=File:\u0641\u0627\u062c\u0639\u0647 \u0642\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u0627\u0628\u0648\u0631 - panoramio.jpg|coordinates={{coord|36.0987|58.9715|type:event|display=inline,title}}|date={{Start date|2004|02|18|df=yes}}|country=[[Iran]]|location=Khayyam|deaths=295|location_city=Nishapur|caption=Khayyam burning after the incident|image_alt=In twilight against snow capped mountains, two firefighters walk through a field flanked by burning rubble of the village|injuries=460|cause=}}{{no footnotes|date=February 2011}}The '''Neishapur train disaster''' was a large explosion in the village of [[Khayyam,_Nishapur|Khayyam]], near [[Nishapur]]  in [[Iran]], on 18 February 2004. Nearly 300 people were killed<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3498851.stm|title=Iran train blast kills hundreds|date=2004-02-18|access-date=2020-04-29|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3487290.stm|title='Error' caused Iran train blast|date=2004-02-25|access-date=2020-04-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the entire village destroyed when runaway train wagons crashed into the community in the middle of the night and exploded, resulting as Iran's deadliest rail disaster to ever occur.\n\n==Beginning of incident==\n\nThe incident began in the city of Nishapur, where 51 railway wagons carrying sulphur, fertiliser, petrol and cotton wool broke loose from their siding at Abu Muslim Station, and rolled down the track for about twenty kilometers, until they derailed and rolled down an embankment into the town of Khayyam.<ref name=\":1\" /> There was nobody manning the wagons, or on board at the time of the crash, but local rescue services from all the neighbouring towns arrived to rescue anybody who might have been trapped inside, and to extinguish several minor fires which had broken out in the wreckage.\n\n==Chemical leak==\n\nThe substances in the wagons were all highly explosive or flammable (although the Iranian railway authority had not classed any of them as \"dangerous\" before the incident), and had leaked following the crash. As the small fires spread, a large crowd of local people, including several local politicians and senior railway officials, gathered to watch the emergency operation.\n\n==Explosion==\n\nDuring the cleanup operation, the cargo of the wagons exploded - reportedly at the equivalent of 180 tons of [[trinitrotoluene|TNT]]<ref name=\":1\" /> - demolishing Khayyam, badly damaging the nearby towns of [[Eyshabad, Nishapur|Eyshabad]], [[Dehnow, Nishapur|Dehnow]] and [[Taqiabad, Nishapur|Taqiabad]], and being felt in the city of [[Mashhad]], 70 kilometers away. The entire village was destroyed, and all of the local emergency services and government personnel were killed or seriously injured in the blast. The wreckage of the train and village continued to burn and explode for several days, despite the cold weather.\n\n==Death toll==\n\nState authorities identified 295 confirmed killed and over 460 injured, including 182 rescue workers and state officials.\n\n==Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps==\nFollowing the blast, troops from the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] were called in and were able to maintain security, whilst hundreds of rescue workers were brought in to help with the injured, the trapped, the missing and the dead.{{Citation Needed|date=September 2011}} Four villages were later described as \"totally destroyed\".{{Citation Needed|date=September 2011}}\n\n==Cause==\n\nInitial reports that \"earth tremors\"<ref name=\":0\" /> started the wagons rolling have since been discredited, and a thorough investigation has so far failed to discover how exactly the wagons were able to travel from Nishapur to Khayyam on their own, why so many highly flammable cargoes were stored and transported together, and why the details of the crash weren't discovered sooner, perhaps in time to arrange an evacuation. A statement from the Iranian Transport Minister [[Ahmad Khorram]] shortly after the incident reported that natural causes could not have caused the disaster, and that an investigation was under way to determine whether it was incompetence or malice by railway staff that allowed the wagons to come loose from where they were parked.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment]] - a 2013 derailment of fuel train and subsequent fire and explosions in the core of a Canadian town, also caused by railcars parked on an incline becoming loose.\n* [[Viareggio train derailment]] - a 2009 derailment of a fuel train in Viareggio, central Italy that caused explosions and fire which killed 32 people.\n* [[Soham rail disaster]] - a 1944 fire and subsequent explosion of an ammunition train near Soham, England.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3487290.stm BBC Report on Aftermath]\n*[http://www.irantour.org/Iran/news/iran_train_blast_neyshaboor_mashad.html Immediate Iranian statement]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/iran/story/0,12858,1150689,00.html Guardian News Report]\n*[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-02/19/content_307559.htm China Daily News Report]\n*[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/4300626 MSNBC News Report]\n*{{in lang|fa}} [http://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/iran/story/2007/11/071127_mf_neyshabur.shtml People responsible for Nishapur train disaster announced by court]\n\n{{2004 railway accidents}}\n\n[[Category:Explosions in 2004]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 2004]]\n[[Category:Derailments in Iran]]\n[[Category:2004 in Iran]]\n[[Category:Explosions in Iran]]\n[[Category:Nishapur|Train disaster]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Iran]]\n[[Category:History of Nishapur]]\n[[Category:Runaway train disasters]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Islamic Republic of Iran Railways]]\n[[Category:February 2004 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Train and subway fires]]\n", "name_user": "Strangerpete", "label": "safe", "comment": "cause/type for infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nishapur_train_disaster"}
{"title_page": "Arfa Khanum Sherwani", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian journalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Arfa Khanum Sherwani\n|image = Arfakhanum.png\n|birth_place  = [[Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1980|11|1}}\n|residence       = \n|alma_mater = [[Aligarh Muslim University]], [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]\n|occupation      = Journalist\n|known_for  = Reporting of Afghan Elections\n|religion      = \n|awards      = Sahitya Samman Award, [[Red Ink Awards|Red Ink Award]], [[Chameli Devi Jain Award for Outstanding Women Mediapersons]]\n}}\n\n'''Arfa Khanum Sherwani''' (born 1 November 1980) is an Indian journalist.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u06cc \u0648\u062c\u06c1 \u0633\u06d2 \u0628\u06be\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0628\u0631\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0631 \u06c1\u06d2 \u0633\u06cc\u06a9\u0648\u0644\u0631\u0632\u0645\u06d4\u0622\u0626\u06cc\u0646 \u06a9\u0627 \u062a\u062d\u0641\u0638 \u0633\u0628\u06be\u06cc \u06a9\u06cc\u0644\u0626\u06d2 \u0636\u0631\u0648\u0631\u06cc : \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641\u06c1 \u062e\u0627\u0646\u0645 \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc |url=https://urdu.millattimes.com/archives/47958 |website=Millat Times |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> She was the only Indian journalist to cover the 2014 Afghan presidential elections.<ref name=\"sawm\">{{cite web |title=About Arfa Khanum |url=https://www.sawmsisters.com/author/akhanum/ |website=Sawm Sisters |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> She has received a [[Red Ink Awards|Red Ink Award]], the ''Sahitya Samman Award'' from the Hindi Academy, and the [[Chameli Devi Jain Award for Outstanding Women Mediapersons]].<ref name=\"newsminute\">{{cite web |title=Journalists Rohini Mohan, Arfa Khanum Sherwani awarded Chameli Devi Jain award |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/journalists-rohini-mohan-arfa-khanum-sherwani-awarded-chameli-devi-jain-award-120147 |website=The News Minute |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ted\">{{cite web |title=About Arfa Khanum Sherwani |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/35802 |website=Ted |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> She is currently senior editor at ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]].''<ref name=\"ahl\">{{cite web |title=Arfa Khanum Sherwani On Indian Muslims And The Media |url=http://ahl-alquran.com/English/show_news.php?main_id=11149 |website=ahl-alquran.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"outlook\">{{cite web |title=2 get Chameli Devi Jain Award for outstanding woman journalist |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/2-get-chameli-devi-jain-award-for-outstanding-woman-journalist/1761361 |website=OutlookIndia.com |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Police Officer Pranav Mahajan slammed journalist Arfa Khanum Sherwani over Nizamuddin Markaz's Tablighi Jamaat congregation.<ref> https://m.freepressjournal.in/article/india/police-officer-pranav-mahajan-slams-wire-journalist-arfa-khanum-sherwani/12bbb053-e182-4da3-b8b8-ef49738288ac </ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nArfa Khanum Sherwani was born on 1 November 1980 in [[Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. She completed her intermediate studies in the city and obtained a [[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc.]] degree from [[Chaudhary Charan Singh University]] in Meerut. Khanum obtained a diploma in journalism from the [[Aligarh Muslim University]]. She completed her doctoral studies from the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref name=\"urdu\">{{cite web |title=\u0628\u0644\u0646\u062f \u0634\u06c1\u0631 \u06a9\u06cc \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0646\u06cc \u2019\u2019\u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641\u06c1 \u062e\u0627\u0646\u0645 \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u2018\u2018 \u0628\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u06a9\u060c \u0628\u06c1\u0627\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0631\u0622\u0632\u0627\u062f \u062e\u0627\u062a\u0648\u0646 \u0635\u062d\u0627\u0641 |url=http://urducity.in/arfa-khanum-sherwani/ |website=UrduCity.in |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKhanum started her career in journalism in 2000.<ref name=\"urdu\" /> She joined ''[[The Pioneer (India)|The Pioneer]]'' as an intern. She later worked with ''[[The Asian Age]]'' and then [[Sahara TV]]. She joined [[NDTV]] as a principal correspondent and news anchor.<ref name=\"sabra\">{{cite web |title=Collective stereotypes |url=https://sabrangindia.in/interview/collective-stereotypes |website=SabrangIndia |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>  She worked with [[Rajya Sabha TV]] until 2017<ref name=\"janta\">{{cite web |title=Anger after Rajya Sabha TV addresses RSS chief Mohan Bhagwat as \u2018His Holiness\u2019 |url=http://www.jantakareporter.com/india/anger-after-rajya-sabha-tv-addresses-rss-chief-mohan-bhagwat-as-his-holiness/191221/ |website=Janta Ka Reporter |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> and is currently a senior editor at ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]].''<ref name=\"outlook\" />\n\nA 42 second clip was cut from a speech Khanum delivered at the [[Aligarh Muslim University]] over [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] and was used to harass her. While talking to the CPJ, she stated that she has received death and rape threats on Facebook, Instagram and Twitter.<ref name=\"deaththreat\">{{cite web |title=Global Scribes' Body Asks BJP Leaders to Stop Online Harassment of The Wire's Arfa Khanum Sherwani |url=https://thewire.in/media/committee-to-protect-journalists-arfa-khanum-sherwani |website=The Wire |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alt\">{{cite web |title=Journalist Arfa Khanum\u2019s speech on CAA shared with distorted interpretation by BJP office-bearers |url=https://www.altnews.in/journalist-arfa-khanums-speech-on-caa-clipped-and-shared-with-communal-overtones/ |website=Alt News |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Chameli Devi Jain Award for Outstanding Women Mediapersons]], 2019<ref name=\"laundry\">{{cite web |title=Rohini Mohan and Arfa Khanum Sherwani win the Chameli Devi Jain Award for outstanding woman journalists |url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2020/03/13/rohini-mohan-and-arfa-khanum-sherwani-win-the-chameli-devi-jain-award-for-outstanding-woman-journalists |website=News Laundry |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Sahitya Samman<ref name=\"ted\">{{cite web |title=About Arfa Khanum Sherwani |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/35802 |website=Ted |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Red Ink Awards|Red Ink Award]]<ref name=\"okhla\">{{cite web |title=Okhla-based journalist Arfa wins journalism award |url=https://www.okhlatimes.com/okhla-arfa-award/ |website=Okhla Times |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jamia Millia Islamia alumni]]\n[[Category:Aligarh Muslim University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chaudhary Charan Singh University alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian women journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian journalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Arfa Khanum Sherwani\n|image = Arfakhanum.png\n|birth_place  = [[Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1980|11|1}}\n|residence       = \n|alma_mater = [[Aligarh Muslim University]], [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]\n|occupation      = Journalist\n|known_for  = Reporting of Afghan Elections\n|religion      = \n|awards      = Sahitya Samman Award, [[Red Ink Awards|Red Ink Award]], [[Chameli Devi Jain Award for Outstanding Women Mediapersons]]\n}}\n\n'''Arfa Khanum Sherwani''' (born 1 November 1980) is an Indian journalist.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u06cc \u0648\u062c\u06c1 \u0633\u06d2 \u0628\u06be\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0628\u0631\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0631 \u06c1\u06d2 \u0633\u06cc\u06a9\u0648\u0644\u0631\u0632\u0645\u06d4\u0622\u0626\u06cc\u0646 \u06a9\u0627 \u062a\u062d\u0641\u0638 \u0633\u0628\u06be\u06cc \u06a9\u06cc\u0644\u0626\u06d2 \u0636\u0631\u0648\u0631\u06cc : \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641\u06c1 \u062e\u0627\u0646\u0645 \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc |url=https://urdu.millattimes.com/archives/47958 |website=Millat Times |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> She was the only Indian journalist to cover the 2014 Afghan presidential elections.<ref name=\"sawm\">{{cite web |title=About Arfa Khanum |url=https://www.sawmsisters.com/author/akhanum/ |website=Sawm Sisters |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> She has received a [[Red Ink Awards|Red Ink Award]], the ''Sahitya Samman Award'' from the Hindi Academy, and the [[Chameli Devi Jain Award for Outstanding Women Mediapersons]].<ref name=\"newsminute\">{{cite web |title=Journalists Rohini Mohan, Arfa Khanum Sherwani awarded Chameli Devi Jain award |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/journalists-rohini-mohan-arfa-khanum-sherwani-awarded-chameli-devi-jain-award-120147 |website=The News Minute |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ted\">{{cite web |title=About Arfa Khanum Sherwani |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/35802 |website=Ted |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> She is currently senior editor at ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]].''<ref name=\"ahl\">{{cite web |title=Arfa Khanum Sherwani On Indian Muslims And The Media |url=http://ahl-alquran.com/English/show_news.php?main_id=11149 |website=ahl-alquran.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"outlook\">{{cite web |title=2 get Chameli Devi Jain Award for outstanding woman journalist |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/2-get-chameli-devi-jain-award-for-outstanding-woman-journalist/1761361 |website=OutlookIndia.com |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nArfa Khanum Sherwani was born on 1 November 1980 in [[Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. She completed her intermediate studies in the city and obtained a [[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc.]] degree from [[Chaudhary Charan Singh University]] in Meerut. Khanum obtained a diploma in journalism from the [[Aligarh Muslim University]]. She completed her doctoral studies from the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref name=\"urdu\">{{cite web |title=\u0628\u0644\u0646\u062f \u0634\u06c1\u0631 \u06a9\u06cc \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0646\u06cc \u2019\u2019\u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641\u06c1 \u062e\u0627\u0646\u0645 \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u2018\u2018 \u0628\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u06a9\u060c \u0628\u06c1\u0627\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0631\u0622\u0632\u0627\u062f \u062e\u0627\u062a\u0648\u0646 \u0635\u062d\u0627\u0641 |url=http://urducity.in/arfa-khanum-sherwani/ |website=UrduCity.in |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKhanum started her career in journalism in 2000.<ref name=\"urdu\" /> She joined ''[[The Pioneer (India)|The Pioneer]]'' as an intern. She later worked with ''[[The Asian Age]]'' and then [[Sahara TV]]. She joined [[NDTV]] as a principal correspondent and news anchor.<ref name=\"sabra\">{{cite web |title=Collective stereotypes |url=https://sabrangindia.in/interview/collective-stereotypes |website=SabrangIndia |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>  She worked with [[Rajya Sabha TV]] until 2017<ref name=\"janta\">{{cite web |title=Anger after Rajya Sabha TV addresses RSS chief Mohan Bhagwat as \u2018His Holiness\u2019 |url=http://www.jantakareporter.com/india/anger-after-rajya-sabha-tv-addresses-rss-chief-mohan-bhagwat-as-his-holiness/191221/ |website=Janta Ka Reporter |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> and is currently a senior editor at ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]].''<ref name=\"outlook\" />\n\nA 42 second clip was cut from a speech Khanum delivered at the [[Aligarh Muslim University]] over [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] and was used to harass her. While talking to the CPJ, she stated that she has received death and rape threats on Facebook, Instagram and Twitter.<ref name=\"deaththreat\">{{cite web |title=Global Scribes' Body Asks BJP Leaders to Stop Online Harassment of The Wire's Arfa Khanum Sherwani |url=https://thewire.in/media/committee-to-protect-journalists-arfa-khanum-sherwani |website=The Wire |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alt\">{{cite web |title=Journalist Arfa Khanum\u2019s speech on CAA shared with distorted interpretation by BJP office-bearers |url=https://www.altnews.in/journalist-arfa-khanums-speech-on-caa-clipped-and-shared-with-communal-overtones/ |website=Alt News |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Chameli Devi Jain Award for Outstanding Women Mediapersons]], 2019<ref name=\"laundry\">{{cite web |title=Rohini Mohan and Arfa Khanum Sherwani win the Chameli Devi Jain Award for outstanding woman journalists |url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2020/03/13/rohini-mohan-and-arfa-khanum-sherwani-win-the-chameli-devi-jain-award-for-outstanding-woman-journalists |website=News Laundry |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Sahitya Samman<ref name=\"ted\">{{cite web |title=About Arfa Khanum Sherwani |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/35802 |website=Ted |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Red Ink Awards|Red Ink Award]]<ref name=\"okhla\">{{cite web |title=Okhla-based journalist Arfa wins journalism award |url=https://www.okhlatimes.com/okhla-arfa-award/ |website=Okhla Times |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jamia Millia Islamia alumni]]\n[[Category:Aligarh Muslim University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chaudhary Charan Singh University alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian women journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n", "name_user": "49.37.143.88", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arfa_Khanum_Sherwani"}
{"title_page": "Kyle Eastmond", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Kyle Eastmond\n|fullname       = \n|nickname       = Kylie, Klynt Eastwood, Arnold\n|image          = Kyle Eastmond Bath.jpg\n|image_size     = \n|position       = {{rlp|SH|SO|CE|FB}}\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1989|7|17|df=yes}}<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.saintsrlfc.com/player/44|publisher=saintsrlfc.com|accessdate=17 August 2017|title=Kyle Eastmond}}</ref>\n|birth_place  = [[Oldham]], [[Greater Manchester]], England\n|height       = {{convert|1.70|m|ftin|abbr=on|order=flip}} \n|weight       = {{convert|85|kg|stlb|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.saintsrlfc.com/team/73|title=Meet the Teams First Team Players|year=2011|work=web page|publisher=Saints RFC|accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref>\n|club1        = [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]]\n|year1start   = 2007\n|year1end     = 11 \n|appearances1 = 74\n|tries1       = 39\n|goals1       = 137\n|fieldgoals1  = 3\n|points1      = 433\n|teamA        = [[England national rugby league team|England]]\n|yearAstart   = 2009\n|yearAend     = \n|appearancesA = 4\n|triesA       = 1\n|goalsA       = 0\n|fieldgoalsA  = 0\n|pointsA      = 4\n| ru_position     = [[Inside Centre|Centre]], [[Rugby union positions#15. Fullback|Fullback]]\n| ru_club1        = [[Bath Rugby|Bath]]\n| ru_year1start   = 2011\n| ru_year1end     = 16\n| ru_appearances1 = 72\n| ru_tries1       = 16 \n| ru_goals1       = 0\n| ru_fieldgoals1  = 0\n| ru_points1      = 80\n| ru_club2        = [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]]\n| ru_year2start   = 2016\n| ru_year2end     = 2018\n| ru_appearances2 = 23\n| ru_tries2       = 4\n| ru_goals2       = 0\n| ru_fieldgoals2  = 0\n| ru_points2      = 20\n| ru_club3        = [[Leicester Tigers]]\n| ru_year3start   = 2018\n| ru_year3end     = present\n| ru_appearances3 = 31\n| ru_tries3       = 3\n| ru_goals3       = 0\n| ru_fieldgoals3  = 0\n| ru_points3      = 15\n| ru_teamA        = [[England national rugby union team|England]]\n| ru_yearAstart   = 2013\n| ru_yearAend     = 2014\n| ru_appearancesA = 6\n| ru_triesA       = \n| ru_goalsA       = \n| ru_fieldgoalsA  =\n| ru_pointsA      = 5\n|updated        = 29 April 2020\n|new            = yes\n|source         = <ref name=\"Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/kyle-eastmond/summary.html|title=Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org|publisher=rugbyleagueproject.org|date=31 December 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"England Statistics at englandrl.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandrl.co.uk/player_records?search=Eastmond&submit=Go&c=England|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131211141125/http://www.englandrl.co.uk/player_records?search=Eastmond&submit=Go&c=England|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 December 2013|title=England Statistics at englandrl.co.uk|publisher=englandrl.co.uk|date=31 December 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Kyle Ovid Eastmond''' (born 17 July 1989)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/england/rugby/player/156773.html|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=1 August 2018|title=ESPN profile}}</ref> is professional [[rugby union]] who plays for [[Leicester Tigers]] in [[Premiership Rugby]]. He is a former professional [[rugby league]] footballer who played for [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] in the [[Super League]], and has represented England internationally in both [[England national rugby league team|rugby league]] and [[England national rugby union team|rugby union]]. In rugby union he has also played professionally for [[Bath Rugby|Bath]] and [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]].\n\nEastmond has been compared to [[Australian national rugby league team|Australian]] international [[Scott Prince]], because of his darting runs to the line and a good kicking game. He has also got a keen eye for a gap in the defensive line.\n\n==Early life==\nKyle attended the Parish Church CEVA School, Oldham and [[the Radclyffe School]], Oldham.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/11/roughyeds-news/30811/roughyeds-in-state-of-flux|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724003404/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/11/roughyeds-news/30811/roughyeds-in-state-of-flux|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-24|publisher=oldham-chronicle.co.uk|date=2009-10-06|accessdate=2009-10-20|title=Roughyeds in 'state of flux'}}</ref>\n\nEastmond is the cousin of former professional [[rugby league]] footballer; [[Miles Greenwood]].<ref name=\"Rugby league: Fax is Miles better for me: Greenwood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/sport/rugby-league-fax-is-miles-better-for-me-greenwood-1-1916299|title=Rugby league: Fax is Miles better for me: Greenwood|publisher=Halifax Courier|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> Kyle is also related to [[Sutton United F.C.|Sutton United]]'s [[Craig Eastmond]], who is his cousin. He has supported Manchester United since childhood.\n\n==Rugby League career==\n\n===Early career===\nDuring high school kyle Eastmond began his rugby career playing rugby league for Oldham St Annes but in 2007, Kyle Eastmond was promoted to training with the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] first team squad.\n\n===2008-09===\nIn 2008, he was given the number 24 jersey and made a spectacular early impression in the traditional [[Good Friday]] fixture with [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], scoring a late try and a goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/mar/26/rugbyleague.sthelens1|title=Rugby league: Modest Eastmond on fast track to become new Jason Robinson|first=Guardian|last=Staff|date=26 March 2008|accessdate=31 January 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> He made 13 appearances in this season scoring 6 tries. He was then compared to [[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Jason Robinson]] for his general attributes, and with his size finds it easy to duck under any oncoming opposition which helped him make 778m.\n[[File:Kyle Eastmond.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Eastmond playing for Saints against the [[Wigan Warriors]]]]\nIn 2009, Kyle became an influential player for the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]] side. He may have played one less game than in 2008, but he scored 8 tries, 30 goals (18 more than the previous year), 7 try assists, he gained 899m and made more clean breaks.\n\nKyle capped off an impressive year in 2009 by scoring all of Saints' 10 points in the [[2009 Super League Grand Final]] defeat by [[Leeds Rhinos|Leeds]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"sky-gf-report\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Rugby-League-Super-League-Leeds-Rhinos-St-Helens-Old-Trafford-Grand-Final/Article/200910215403491|title=Rhinos Take Super League Title|date=2009-10-11|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burke|first=David|title=Smith's Crisp|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/more-sport/2009/10/11/smith-s-crisp-115875-21738035|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=AFP|title=Leeds makes it Super League hat-trick|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-10-11/leeds-makes-it-super-league-hat-trick/1098564|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] News|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]]|title=Leeds claim third successive Grand Final|url=http://www.nrl.com/NewsViews/LatestNews/NewsArticle/tabid/10874/newsId/57077/Default.aspx|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[National Rugby League|nrl]]|date=11 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003225647/http://www.nrl.com/NewsViews/LatestNews/NewsArticle/tabid/10874/newsId/57077/Default.aspx|archive-date=3 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Linfoot|first=Ben|title=Grand Final: Leeds Rhinos 18 St Helens 10|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugbyleague/match_commentary/0,19936,11070_3204177,00.html|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=Sky Sports|date=10 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Correspondent|title=Potter refuses to blame video ref|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/2009/10/12/potter-refuses-to-blame-video-ref-100252-24906251|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]]|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|title=St Helens 10-18 Leeds Rhinos|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/8290503.stm|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Third time unlucky as Saints fail to halt Rhinos' charge to title|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/2009/10/12/third-time-unlucky-as-saints-fail-to-halt-rhinos-charge-to-title-92534-24906166|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=Liverpool Daily Post|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sinfield hails winning culture|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/latest/2009/10/11/sinfield-hails-winning-culture-115875-21738669|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Rob|title=Lee Smith targets place in England rugby union team after Grand Final victory|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/6299292/Lee-Smith-targets-place-in-England-rugby-union-team-after-Grand-Final-victory.html|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sinfield hails historic title win|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/super_league/leeds/8301354.stm|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leeds Rhinos fans in homecoming welcome|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/central-leeds/video_leeds_rhinos_fans_in_homecoming_welcome_1_2230845|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/8290503.stm\n|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|date=2008-10-10|accessdate=2009-10-20|title=St Helens 10-18 Leeds Rhinos}}</ref>\n\nHe was then selected for [[England national rugby league team|England]] in the [[2009 Four Nations]] tournament and made his international d\u00e9but against [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]] in a warm-up game. In December 2009, Eastmond signed a new two-year contract with St Helens that ended at the end of the 2011 Super League season.\n\n===2010-11===\nAfter [[Sean Long]] left [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] to join [[Hull F.C.]] at the end of the 2009 season, Kyle became the new number 7 for Saints. He started the year very well before injuries hit him for the 2nd half of the season. Although he still managed to make 19 appearances scoring 15 tries. He scored 63 goal kicks missing 18, and kicked 2 drop goals. He made a total of 1615m. Every time he came back from injury he seem to aggravate it. Therefore, meaning he missed the [[2010 Super League Grand Final|Grand Final]] defeat by [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]]. [[Matty Smith]], now of [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], returned from his loan spell at Salford for the play-offs and featured in the final.\n\nIn early 2011 Eastmond was linked with a move to [[Rugby Union]]. Kyle started the season poorly and with fans getting on his back. However, on 28 February 2011 both the club and coach [[Royce Simmons]], confirmed he was to leave Saints. It was revealed that Kyle had signed a three-year deal with [[Bath Rugby]], Eastmond has promised to be 100% committed to his current club for the rest of the season.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/606/A81958594\n|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|date=2011-02-28|accessdate=2011-02-28|title=Comfrimed: Eastond to Bath Rugby Union}}</ref> Commenting on the move, Bath Director of Rugby [[Ian McGeechan|Sir Ian McGeechan]] said he envisions Eastmond playing at [[Centre (rugby union)|centre]].\n\nOn 16 March 2011 it was announced on the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] website that he had been suspended by the club pending an investigation into serious misconduct. The club also said that no further comments will be made until the completion of the investigation. It was confirmed by the club that he made an inappropriate gesture to his home fans, and it looked unlikely he would ever play in the red V again, especially after the emergence of scrum-half sensation [[Jonny Lomax]], and stand-off [[Lee Gaskell]]. He was dropped to the under-18s team. However injuries struck Saints, and they called upon Kyle to fill in. He was playing under difficult circumstances, with Saints fans booing him with every touch of the ball, however he made a decent return. In July 2011 he successfully made the switch from the halfbacks to fullback, scoring 2 tries against [[Wakefield Trinity]] on 9 July. Since then Kyle has regained his confidence and is playing in a similar way to the 2008-09 seasons. He has so far managed 15 appearances and scored 5 tries, but reduced to just 4 goal kicks (3 missed kicks) due to [[Jamie Foster]] replacing him as the club's kicker.\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Bath===\nKyle joined Bath, when he moved in October 2011, after his contract finished at Saints. At Bath he played well and picked up Rugby Union quickly meaning that in 2013, Kyle was selected to play for the England Saxons. During the 13/14 season, Eastmond formed a crucial partnership with George Ford, which led to Baths resurgence to the top of Aviva Premiership, he would then get selected for the main England side in the 2014 Autumn internationals but missed out on selection to England's World Cup squad to then Bath Club colleague Sam Burgess.\n\n===Wasps===\nAfter a poor season by the whole team after the World Cup he left Bath to join Wasps who were emerging as top team and had bought a new stadium in the Ricoh Arena, Coventry. His period with Wasps was blighted by injury, and resultantly playing second-choice often from the bench to other more reliable players.\n\n===Leicester===\nOn 1 August 2018 Leicester Tigers announced the signing of Eastmond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/45030592|title=Kyle Eastmond: Leicester sign utility back|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=1 August 2018|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nEastmond was selected in the [[England national rugby union team|England]] squad to tour America in the summer of 2013. He played his first game in the uncapped match against Barbarians on 26 May 2013, scoring a try shortly after coming off the bench as a replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/22673139|title=BBC Sport - England 40-12 Barbarians: Freddie Burns shines in win|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=2013-05-26|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n\nHe won his first England cap as a replacement in the first test against [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web|author=ChronSport|url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Kyle-Eastmond-earns-England-cap-victory-Argentina/story-19240468-detail/story.html|title=Bath Rugby back Kyle Eastmond earned his first England cap in the 32-3 victory over Argentina|publisher=Bath Chronicle|date=2013-06-10|accessdate=2014-02-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221220759/http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Kyle-Eastmond-earns-England-cap-victory-Argentina/story-19240468-detail/story.html|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nEastmond made his first start for England on 15 June 2013, replacing Lions call-up [[Billy Twelvetrees]]. He scored a try in the 51-26 victory over Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|last=Standley|first=James|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/22915126|title=BBC Sport - Argentina 26-51 England|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=2013-06-15|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.wasps.co.uk/players-staff/player/kyle-eastmond Wasps profile]\n*(archived by web.archive.org) [https://web.archive.org/web/20111024184430/http://www.bathrugby.com/team/first-fifteen-squad/kyle-eastmond Bath profile]\n*[http://www.saints.org.uk/saints/player.php?num=16635 Saints Heritage Society profile]\n\n{{Leicester Tigers squad}}\n{{England 2009 Rugby League Four Nations squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eastmond, Kyle}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Bath Rugby players]]\n[[Category:Dual-code rugby internationals]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:England national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:English rugby league players]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Radclyffe School]]\n[[Category:People from Oldham]]\n[[Category:St Helens R.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leicester Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league halfbacks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Kyle Eastmond\n|fullname       = \n|nickname       = Kylie, Klynt Eastwood, Arnold\n|image          = Kyle Eastmond Bath.jpg\n|image_size     = \n|position       = {{rlp|SH|SO|CE|FB}}\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1989|7|17|df=yes}}<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.saintsrlfc.com/player/44|publisher=saintsrlfc.com|accessdate=17 August 2017|title=Kyle Eastmond}}</ref>\n|birth_place  = [[Oldham]], [[Greater Manchester]], England\n|height       = {{convert|1.70|m|ftin|abbr=on|order=flip}} \n|weight       = {{convert|85|kg|stlb|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.saintsrlfc.com/team/73|title=Meet the Teams First Team Players|year=2011|work=web page|publisher=Saints RFC|accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref>\n|club1        = [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]]\n|year1start   = 2007\n|year1end     = 11 \n|appearances1 = 74\n|tries1       = 39\n|goals1       = 137\n|fieldgoals1  = 3\n|points1      = 433\n|teamA        = [[England national rugby league team|England]]\n|yearAstart   = 2009\n|yearAend     = \n|appearancesA = 4\n|triesA       = 1\n|goalsA       = 0\n|fieldgoalsA  = 0\n|pointsA      = 4\n| ru_position     = [[Inside Centre|Centre]], [[Rugby union positions#15. Fullback|Fullback]]\n| ru_club1        = [[Bath Rugby|Bath]]\n| ru_year1start   = 2011\n| ru_year1end     = 16\n| ru_appearances1 = 72\n| ru_tries1       = 16 \n| ru_goals1       = 0\n| ru_fieldgoals1  = 0\n| ru_points1      = 80\n| ru_club2        = [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]]\n| ru_year2start   = 2016\n| ru_year2end     = 2018\n| ru_appearances2 = 23\n| ru_tries2       = 4\n| ru_goals2       = 0\n| ru_fieldgoals2  = 0\n| ru_points2      = 20\n| ru_club3        = [[Leicester Tigers]]\n| ru_year3start   = 2018\n| ru_year3end     = present\n| ru_appearances3 = 25\n| ru_tries3       = 3\n| ru_goals3       = 0\n| ru_fieldgoals3  = 0\n| ru_points3      = 15\n| ru_teamA        = [[England national rugby union team|England]]\n| ru_yearAstart   = 2013\n| ru_yearAend     = 2014\n| ru_appearancesA = 6\n| ru_triesA       = \n| ru_goalsA       = \n| ru_fieldgoalsA  =\n| ru_pointsA      = 5\n|updated        = 5 January 2020\n|new            = yes\n|source         = <ref name=\"Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/kyle-eastmond/summary.html|title=Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org|publisher=rugbyleagueproject.org|date=31 December 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"England Statistics at englandrl.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.englandrl.co.uk/player_records?search=Eastmond&submit=Go&c=England|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131211141125/http://www.englandrl.co.uk/player_records?search=Eastmond&submit=Go&c=England|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 December 2013|title=England Statistics at englandrl.co.uk|publisher=englandrl.co.uk|date=31 December 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Kyle Ovid Eastmond''' (born 17 July 1989)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/england/rugby/player/156773.html|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=1 August 2018|title=ESPN profile}}</ref> is professional [[rugby union]] who plays for [[Leicester Tigers]] in [[Premiership Rugby]]. He is a former professional [[rugby league]] footballer who played for [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] in the [[Super League]], and has represented England internationally in both [[England national rugby league team|rugby league]] and [[England national rugby union team|rugby union]]. In rugby union he has also played professionally for [[Bath Rugby|Bath]] and [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]].\n\nEastmond has been compared to [[Australian national rugby league team|Australian]] international [[Scott Prince]], because of his darting runs to the line and a good kicking game. He has also got a keen eye for a gap in the defensive line.\n\n==Early life==\nKyle attended the Parish Church CEVA School, Oldham and [[the Radclyffe School]], Oldham.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/11/roughyeds-news/30811/roughyeds-in-state-of-flux|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724003404/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/11/roughyeds-news/30811/roughyeds-in-state-of-flux|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-24|publisher=oldham-chronicle.co.uk|date=2009-10-06|accessdate=2009-10-20|title=Roughyeds in 'state of flux'}}</ref>\n\nEastmond is the cousin of former professional [[rugby league]] footballer; [[Miles Greenwood]].<ref name=\"Rugby league: Fax is Miles better for me: Greenwood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/sport/rugby-league-fax-is-miles-better-for-me-greenwood-1-1916299|title=Rugby league: Fax is Miles better for me: Greenwood|publisher=Halifax Courier|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> Kyle is also related to [[Sutton United F.C.|Sutton United]]'s [[Craig Eastmond]], who is his cousin. He has supported Manchester United since childhood.\n\n==Rugby League career==\n\n===Early career===\nDuring high school kyle Eastmond began his rugby career playing rugby league for Oldham St Annes but in 2007, Kyle Eastmond was promoted to training with the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] first team squad.\n\n===2008-09===\nIn 2008, he was given the number 24 jersey and made a spectacular early impression in the traditional [[Good Friday]] fixture with [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], scoring a late try and a goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/mar/26/rugbyleague.sthelens1|title=Rugby league: Modest Eastmond on fast track to become new Jason Robinson|first=Guardian|last=Staff|date=26 March 2008|accessdate=31 January 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> He made 13 appearances in this season scoring 6 tries. He was then compared to [[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Jason Robinson]] for his general attributes, and with his size finds it easy to duck under any oncoming opposition which helped him make 778m.\n[[File:Kyle Eastmond.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Eastmond playing for Saints against the [[Wigan Warriors]]]]\nIn 2009, Kyle became an influential player for the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]] side. He may have played one less game than in 2008, but he scored 8 tries, 30 goals (18 more than the previous year), 7 try assists, he gained 899m and made more clean breaks.\n\nKyle capped off an impressive year in 2009 by scoring all of Saints' 10 points in the [[2009 Super League Grand Final]] defeat by [[Leeds Rhinos|Leeds]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref name=\"sky-gf-report\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Rugby-League-Super-League-Leeds-Rhinos-St-Helens-Old-Trafford-Grand-Final/Article/200910215403491|title=Rhinos Take Super League Title|date=2009-10-11|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burke|first=David|title=Smith's Crisp|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/more-sport/2009/10/11/smith-s-crisp-115875-21738035|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=AFP|title=Leeds makes it Super League hat-trick|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-10-11/leeds-makes-it-super-league-hat-trick/1098564|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] News|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]]|title=Leeds claim third successive Grand Final|url=http://www.nrl.com/NewsViews/LatestNews/NewsArticle/tabid/10874/newsId/57077/Default.aspx|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[National Rugby League|nrl]]|date=11 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003225647/http://www.nrl.com/NewsViews/LatestNews/NewsArticle/tabid/10874/newsId/57077/Default.aspx|archive-date=3 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Linfoot|first=Ben|title=Grand Final: Leeds Rhinos 18 St Helens 10|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugbyleague/match_commentary/0,19936,11070_3204177,00.html|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=Sky Sports|date=10 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Correspondent|title=Potter refuses to blame video ref|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/2009/10/12/potter-refuses-to-blame-video-ref-100252-24906251|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]]|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|title=St Helens 10-18 Leeds Rhinos|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/8290503.stm|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Third time unlucky as Saints fail to halt Rhinos' charge to title|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/2009/10/12/third-time-unlucky-as-saints-fail-to-halt-rhinos-charge-to-title-92534-24906166|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=Liverpool Daily Post|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sinfield hails winning culture|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/latest/2009/10/11/sinfield-hails-winning-culture-115875-21738669|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=The Daily Mirror|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Rob|title=Lee Smith targets place in England rugby union team after Grand Final victory|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/6299292/Lee-Smith-targets-place-in-England-rugby-union-team-after-Grand-Final-victory.html|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sinfield hails historic title win|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/super_league/leeds/8301354.stm|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leeds Rhinos fans in homecoming welcome|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/central-leeds/video_leeds_rhinos_fans_in_homecoming_welcome_1_2230845|accessdate=22 November 2019|newspaper=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]|date=12 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/8290503.stm\n|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|date=2008-10-10|accessdate=2009-10-20|title=St Helens 10-18 Leeds Rhinos}}</ref>\n\nHe was then selected for [[England national rugby league team|England]] in the [[2009 Four Nations]] tournament and made his international d\u00e9but against [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]] in a warm-up game. In December 2009, Eastmond signed a new two-year contract with St Helens that ended at the end of the 2011 Super League season.\n\n===2010-11===\nAfter [[Sean Long]] left [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] to join [[Hull F.C.]] at the end of the 2009 season, Kyle became the new number 7 for Saints. He started the year very well before injuries hit him for the 2nd half of the season. Although he still managed to make 19 appearances scoring 15 tries. He scored 63 goal kicks missing 18, and kicked 2 drop goals. He made a total of 1615m. Every time he came back from injury he seem to aggravate it. Therefore, meaning he missed the [[2010 Super League Grand Final|Grand Final]] defeat by [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]]. [[Matty Smith]], now of [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], returned from his loan spell at Salford for the play-offs and featured in the final.\n\nIn early 2011 Eastmond was linked with a move to [[Rugby Union]]. Kyle started the season poorly and with fans getting on his back. However, on 28 February 2011 both the club and coach [[Royce Simmons]], confirmed he was to leave Saints. It was revealed that Kyle had signed a three-year deal with [[Bath Rugby]], Eastmond has promised to be 100% committed to his current club for the rest of the season.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/606/A81958594\n|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|date=2011-02-28|accessdate=2011-02-28|title=Comfrimed: Eastond to Bath Rugby Union}}</ref> Commenting on the move, Bath Director of Rugby [[Ian McGeechan|Sir Ian McGeechan]] said he envisions Eastmond playing at [[Centre (rugby union)|centre]].\n\nOn 16 March 2011 it was announced on the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] website that he had been suspended by the club pending an investigation into serious misconduct. The club also said that no further comments will be made until the completion of the investigation. It was confirmed by the club that he made an inappropriate gesture to his home fans, and it looked unlikely he would ever play in the red V again, especially after the emergence of scrum-half sensation [[Jonny Lomax]], and stand-off [[Lee Gaskell]]. He was dropped to the under-18s team. However injuries struck Saints, and they called upon Kyle to fill in. He was playing under difficult circumstances, with Saints fans booing him with every touch of the ball, however he made a decent return. In July 2011 he successfully made the switch from the halfbacks to fullback, scoring 2 tries against [[Wakefield Trinity]] on 9 July. Since then Kyle has regained his confidence and is playing in a similar way to the 2008-09 seasons. He has so far managed 15 appearances and scored 5 tries, but reduced to just 4 goal kicks (3 missed kicks) due to [[Jamie Foster]] replacing him as the club's kicker.\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Bath===\nKyle joined Bath, when he moved in October 2011, after his contract finished at Saints. At Bath he played well and picked up Rugby Union quickly meaning that in 2013, Kyle was selected to play for the England Saxons. During the 13/14 season, Eastmond formed a crucial partnership with George Ford, which led to Baths resurgence to the top of Aviva Premiership, he would then get selected for the main England side in the 2014 Autumn internationals but missed out on selection to England's World Cup squad to then Bath Club colleague Sam Burgess.\n\n===Wasps===\nAfter a poor season by the whole team after the World Cup he left Bath to join Wasps who were emerging as top team and had bought a new stadium in the Ricoh Arena, Coventry. His period with Wasps was blighted by injury, and resultantly playing second-choice often from the bench to other more reliable players.\n\n===Leicester===\nOn 1 August 2018 Leicester Tigers announced the signing of Eastmond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/45030592|title=Kyle Eastmond: Leicester sign utility back|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=1 August 2018|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nEastmond was selected in the [[England national rugby union team|England]] squad to tour America in the summer of 2013. He played his first game in the uncapped match against Barbarians on 26 May 2013, scoring a try shortly after coming off the bench as a replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/22673139|title=BBC Sport - England 40-12 Barbarians: Freddie Burns shines in win|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=2013-05-26|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n\nHe won his first England cap as a replacement in the first test against [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web|author=ChronSport|url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Kyle-Eastmond-earns-England-cap-victory-Argentina/story-19240468-detail/story.html|title=Bath Rugby back Kyle Eastmond earned his first England cap in the 32-3 victory over Argentina|publisher=Bath Chronicle|date=2013-06-10|accessdate=2014-02-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221220759/http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Kyle-Eastmond-earns-England-cap-victory-Argentina/story-19240468-detail/story.html|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nEastmond made his first start for England on 15 June 2013, replacing Lions call-up [[Billy Twelvetrees]]. He scored a try in the 51-26 victory over Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|last=Standley|first=James|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/22915126|title=BBC Sport - Argentina 26-51 England|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|date=2013-06-15|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.wasps.co.uk/players-staff/player/kyle-eastmond Wasps profile]\n*(archived by web.archive.org) [https://web.archive.org/web/20111024184430/http://www.bathrugby.com/team/first-fifteen-squad/kyle-eastmond Bath profile]\n*[http://www.saints.org.uk/saints/player.php?num=16635 Saints Heritage Society profile]\n\n{{Leicester Tigers squad}}\n{{England 2009 Rugby League Four Nations squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eastmond, Kyle}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Bath Rugby players]]\n[[Category:Dual-code rugby internationals]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:England national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:English rugby league players]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Radclyffe School]]\n[[Category:People from Oldham]]\n[[Category:St Helens R.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leicester Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league halfbacks]]\n", "name_user": "Skeene88", "label": "safe", "comment": "updating club stats", "url_page":